  "analysis": {
    "why_cache_aware_routing_matters": [
      "Every LLM inference request starts with prefill \u2014 processing the entire input context before generating the first output token.",
      "Prefill time scales linearly with context length: 88ms at 500 tokens, 758ms at 8000 tokens.",
      "With prefix caching, vLLM stores computed KV blocks. A cache hit skips prefill entirely, producing constant ~35-44ms TTFT regardless of context length.",
      "Standard Kubernetes round-robin load balancing scatters requests randomly across pods. Each pod must re-compute prefill for prompts it has not seen.",
      "llm-d's cache-aware routing sends requests to the pod that already has the KV cache for that prompt, turning every request into a cache hit."
    ],
    "key_findings": [
      "17.3x TTFT speedup at 8K tokens \u2014 the advantage scales with the context window LLMs actually use in production.",
      "75% TTFT reduction under 10-concurrent-session load \u2014 the benefit is even MORE dramatic under production concurrency.",
      "Cache-aware routing converges at request 1 vs request 4 for round-robin (one per pod). With 100 pods in production, RR needs 100 cold starts.",
      "Agentic chains show compounding benefit: each step reuses ALL prior context. With round-robin, every step must re-prefill context it has already computed on another pod.",
      "Steady-state TTFT with cache-aware routing stays flat (52-61ms) even as conversation context grows, while round-robin oscillates (179-289ms).",
